      "text": "**Defining the System Scope**\n\nI\u0027m now zeroing in on defining the precise system scope, and it includes building a custom polling and testing system for the IB portal, which will be implemented in 1C-Bitrix, but use a modern, glassmorphism UI, vanilla JS, and custom data storage in IBlocks, rather than the standard approach. I need to fully understand these requirements.\n\n\n**Clarifying Bitrix Implementation**\n\nI\u0027m now focusing on how to configure the Bitrix IBlocks, since I need to provide the files and instructions, as the user cannot configure these themselves. I have a clearer IBlock structure, starting with Tests (test names), and Questions (linked to tests). Questions will have text properties, a link to the Tests IBlock, and an ANSWERS property. This property will be multiple strings (or JSON) for answers and the correct one.\n\n\n**Refining IBlock Structure**\n\nI\u0027m revisiting the IBlock structure to streamline it for the user. I\u0027ve decided on three IBlocks: \"Tests\" (test names), \"Questions\" (linked to tests), and \"Results\" (user submissions). For Questions, the structure is settled. Questions have text properties, a link to the Tests IBlock, and an ANSWERS property (multiple strings) with a CORRECT_ANSWER (index). Results stores user submissions, linking to the relevant Test and tracking the SCORE. I\u0027m focusing on simplicity and ease of user configuration in this model.\n\n\n**Simplifying IBlock Configuration**\n\nI\u0027ve streamlined the IBlock structure even further. Now, it\u0027s just two IBlocks: \"Tests and Questions\" (where Sections are Tests, Elements are Questions with text, answers, and the correct index) and \"Test Results\" (for user submissions with user name, test name, and score). This reduces complexity for the user. I\u0027m focusing on the implementation plan, with data structure instructions and the PHP files for test listing and AJAX handling. The frontend shouldn\u0027t calculate scores.\n\n\n**Finalizing Score Calculation**\n\nI\u0027ve decided to let the frontend handle score calculation for faster UI updates, sending the `{userName, testId, testName, score, total}` data to the backend for storage. I am now embedding questions directly as a JSON object within the page to optimize initial loading time, reducing the need for additional AJAX calls. I\u0027ve begun working on the IBlock setup instructions to detail how the \u0027Polls\u0027 IBlock Sections for tests, Elements for questions with \u0027ANSWERS\u0027 and \u0027CORRECT_INDEX\u0027 properties, and the \u0027Poll Results\u0027 IBlock.\n\n\n**Implementing the IBlock Structure**\n\nI\u0027m now writing the core PHP files: `/ib-test/polls/index.php` and `/ib-test/polls/ajax.php`. I\u0027m using `CIBlockSection::GetList` and `CIBlockElement::GetList` to efficiently retrieve test and question data. I\u0027m building a `window.ibTestsData` JS object to hold everything, so the frontend renders cards and the modal correctly. `/ib-test/polls/ajax.php` receives and saves user results using `CIBlockElement::Add`. The user experience should be seamless, with cards, modals, and AJAX communication. I plan to use a glassmorphism modal, as well.\n\n\n**Finalizing the Documentation**\n\nI\u0027m now writing the instructions, meticulously structuring them into \"Instruction for the Admin,\" \"Frontend (index.php),\" and \"Backend (ajax.php).\" I\u0027m ensuring all Vanilla JS and CSS align with the previous styles. During drafting, I\u0027m making sure to include necessary Bitrix includes for AJAX and IBlock module loading. I\u0027m also ensuring the poll modal\u0027s CSS is isolated.\n\n\n**Optimizing Data Retrieval**\n\nI\u0027m now refining the data retrieval logic within the PHP files to guarantee the correct question data is retrieved and processed. I realize `CIBlockElement::GetList` can retrieve multiple properties correctly, but not if using specific values. I\u0027m focusing on the safest way to iterate properties with this method. I must optimize data retrieval and build an array, so I can pass it to the frontend via JSON.\n\n\n",
